## 🛠️ Phase 1 – Advanced DSA + System Design + Core Subjects Depth  
**(Months 1–12 of Third Year)**

### 1. Advanced DSA Mastery
**Focus:** Company-tagged problems, hard patterns, optimization under constraints

**Monthly Breakdown**

**Months 1–3**
- Advanced Graphs: Dijkstra, Bellman-Ford, Floyd-Warshall, MST (Kruskal/Prim), Strongly Connected Components
- Advanced DP: 2D DP, bitmask DP, digit DP, DP on trees/graphs
- Trie & Suffix Structures: Trie for prefix search, word break II, longest common substring

**Months 4–6**
- Segment Tree & Fenwick Tree basics + applications
- Binary Indexed Tree for range queries
- Advanced Greedy + Binary Search on Answer
- Hard Backtracking + Pruning (N-Queens variants, sudoku solver optimizations)

**Months 7–9**
- Hard Two Pointers + Sliding Window (minimum window substring variants)
- Hard Heaps + Priority Queue (median finder, task scheduler II)
- Advanced Trees: Heavy-Light Decomposition intro, centroid decomposition basics

**Months 10–12**
- Company-specific marathons (Google, Amazon, Microsoft tagged hard)
- Mock contests (LeetCode weekly/biweekly, Codeforces rounds)
- Optimization techniques: bit manipulation tricks, math optimizations

**Targets**
- Total: 1000–1500+ problems
- Medium: 600–900
- Hard: 250–400+
- LeetCode: 300+ hard solved, Knight+ rating

**Resources**
- Striver SDE Sheet + A2Z DSA Sheet
- Love Babbar 450 + company-specific lists
- takeUforward hard series
- NeetCode All + LeetCode Explore (hard cards)
- CP-Algorithms.com for advanced topics

### 2. System Design – Low-Level & High-Level Basics
**Low-Level Design (LLD / OOP Design)**
- Design patterns deep: Strategy, Observer, Decorator, Singleton (thread-safe), Factory/Abstract Factory
- Design vending machine, parking lot, chess game, elevator system, library management
- SOLID + DRY + KISS principles in real code

**High-Level Design (HLD / System Design)**
- URL shortener (TinyURL), Instagram/Twitter feed, WhatsApp messaging, Uber backend, Netflix recommendation
- Key concepts: Load balancing, caching (Redis), databases (sharding, replication), queues (Kafka/RabbitMQ), microservices vs monolith, CAP theorem basics

**Resources**
- Grokking the System Design Interview (Educative)
- ByteByteGo YouTube
- System Design Primer GitHub repo
- Striver system design playlist

### 3. Core Subjects – Advanced Interview Level
**OOP & Design**
- Design a complete system using OOP (e.g., ride-sharing app entities)

**DBMS Advanced**
- Query optimization, execution plans, sharding vs partitioning
- NoSQL vs SQL trade-offs, eventual consistency

**OS Advanced**
- Linux internals basics (fork/exec, signals, threads in Linux)
- Kernel vs user space, scheduling in Linux

**CN Advanced**
- WebSockets vs long polling, CDN working, HTTPS handshake (TLS 1.3)
- Load balancing algorithms (round-robin, least connection)

